description.narrative:
Results achieved in the program reported for 2021 are:
- Successful organization of the LKDF Forum 2021 with 648 registrations from 96 countries from all over the world, receiving over 104,000 impressions (over 75k impressions on Twitter and over 17k on LinkedIn) and over 2,400 engagements on social media; within the LKDF Forum 2021, successful organization of the LKDF Hackathon with a total of 184 applications, of which 21 were selected as young participants and 6 as mentors to form 6 teams, whose solutions were evaluated by a jury of 4 jurors;
- Co-organization and/or participation as a speaker to 9 high-level events from partners;
- Worked with 16 partners (7 existing and 9 new partners) in advocacy, project development and training initiatives;
- Development of 7 new PPDP projects, which received approval, and initiation of 4 new PPDP project concept proposals;
- Formulation of 2 projects following the MSD approach in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and Liberia and publication of an MSD-related paper From pilot to scale"
- A Framework for development practitioners for market driven vocational training using PPDPs as case study;
- Finalization of the LKDF 2.0 Advocacy and Communication Strategy 2020-2022 and of the LKDF Brand Book containing the new LKDF visual identity;
- Expansion of its advocacy and outreach activities: 14 social media campaigns, 3 publications around the theme of the LKDF Forum, 27 articles published on the LKDF website and its partners, 22 videos published (internally produced and sent by external contributors) and reached over 1,000 subscribers through its mailing list;
- Collaboration with its partner Impakter to develop a project proposal for a methodology to that assesses the effect of present and future skill development efforts on the SDGs.
During the reporting period, the use of digital technologies including the hosting of virtual meetings and events, proved to be very effective and successful in engaging stakeholders and bring in new partners. It has also been proven worth investing on
advocacy and outreach activities as they lead to more partnership opportunities. As a result from the LKDF Forum, new partners such as the IFC, the Government of Namibia and the African Union, reached out to the LKDF Secretariat to explore possible synergies and ways of cooperation such as joint campaigns and project development and/or involvement. Innovative initiatives such as new financing modalities like outcome-based contracts, youth hackathons, methodologies to track the SDG compliance of the private sector, bring a particular value to the work that the LKDF is delivering on bridging the industrial skills gap. Continuous communication with other UNIDO teams, PPDPs and external stakeholders and maintaining good relationships at all levels should be maintained and reinforced and will be continued during the next reporting period.

Sida assesses that the LKDF has a potential to be a strong global stakeholder for PPDP development globally and are on track in achieving sustainable results according to plan.
Sida will closely follow the knowledge development and usage of the MSD approach with the program since the systematic approach is crucial in strengthening ownership and results on the local level.
During the next reporting period the main emphasis of LKDF will remain on advocacy and partnership activities, on the LKDF website restructuring, on the organization of the LKDF Forum 2022, on new PPDP development, on training partners on MSD and on its application at PPDP level. The LKDF will continue on designing of a monitoring system to apply to skill training activities and to assess the impact of skills development on the SDGs.
